            <bioghist id="aspace_34c4e07941ce4999f5378bc9da025681">
               <head>Bay Area Raza Coalition for Health (BARCH)</head>
               <p>BARCH was a health project that recruited Latine students from low economic status households to enroll in health professional schools. The program was funded by the Comprehensive Health Manpower Training Act of 1971, which provided federal financial assistance to schools of medicine, osteopathy, dentistry, veterinary medicine, optometry, podiatry, pharmacy, and public health. BARCH partnered with six clinics and thirty-one colleges and university across seven states to enroll students.</p>
            </bioghist>
            <bioghist id="aspace_4d169fb22db6481ac91c360440065379">
               <head>La Raza Law Students Association </head>
               <p>La Raza Law Students Association was a nation-wide group created to advocate and empower Latine communities by encouraging students to practice law and transform the country structurally through policy change. Local state chapters of the association made brochures and other resources for students on topics such as the law school application process, law schools in the US and abroad, financial aid, and LSAT preparation programs.</p>
            </bioghist>
            <scopecontent id="aspace_d4009f34031497754572f0192e6a4cc7">
               <head>Scope and Contents</head>
               <p>This accession contains newsletters, pamphlets, and flyers made by and for Chicano students in California during the 1970s and early 1980s. Included in the materials are two issues of <title>
                     <part>Rasca Tripas</part>
                  </title>, a bilingual newsletter published by La Raza Student Union of Merritt College. The newsletters contain essays on Palestinian liberation, the Cuban revolution, the emergence of Chicano Studies, the grape-picker struggle, and increased criminalization of Black and Brown people.</p>
               <p>Also included are brochures by La Raza Law Students Association and by Bay Area Raza Coalition for Health. Lastly, there is a flyer for a benefit dance at Pioneer High School in Eastside L.A. featuring musicians El Chicano, Tierra, and DJ Tommy Arenas.</p>
            </scopecontent>
